I just want to point out that the results may be greatly influenced by the effort you put on the test. For exemple sometimes, I didn't exactly see the colors but I had to put some effort to not focus on a single point (because when you focus on a single point, you only see black around your point) but to try to distinguish the whole picture of the circle. This way, if you are focused enough, you can see the hole in circle, even if you may have doubts that you may see 100% right. 

So my point is, a lot of people may casually take the test without putting the enough amount of efforts to distinguish hard parts of the test. So it may mess up with the result. The best you can do I think, is consider this test only as an indicator with an error margin.

I seem to also be way more sensitive to flickering than most people. 
Back in 2001, there was a discussion in the Quakeworld community about how many frames per second the human eye can actually perceive, with some claiming as low as ~30 per second. To settle it we set up (double-blind) tests with 5 identical computers/monitors running at 60Hz, 85Hz, 100Hz, 125Hz and 160Hz respectively, vsync turned on. (the graphics cards at the time could put out >300 frames per second in the game we used)
I and most of my teammates could easily point out which was which by just running around in the game a few seconds. Friends who had not been playing competitively for years, however, got very varied results. Some couldn't even tell 60Hz one apart from the others.

I once got a perfect score on another online color-distinguishing test, so this isn't particularly surprising to me. It was over a year ago so I don't remember which test it was, but I don't remember ever having taken another color distinguishing test online except for simple colorblindness tests. The test was one of the ones in Google Images that has a black background and requires dragging color squares into order.

I mentioned in my other comment that defocusing my eyes seemed to help, and I think that might be an important factor for your test due to the form factor; I suspect it might be possible that, when focusing on a small section of the grid rather than defocusing and looking at the image overall, "outlier" grid cell colors might mislead some people. I also think that it would be very interesting to test how effective people are if they're encouraged not to select "I can't tell!" for all ambiguous images.

Related to that, I don't know how you're scoring results on the ambiguous end of the test, so I don't know if a participant who guesses randomly for images they feel uncertain about would do better given that they have no actual vision of the answer, or do worse given that they have no action vision of the answer; versus do better given that they can actually see the circle, versus do worse given that they can actually see the circle. I trust you're taking this into account, but as a test-taker this makes me suspicious of the accuracy of the "color age" guess.

Good incentive based psychology behind this test. You hook them with an offer, which later becomes a proposed trade, of information about themselves. The information offered is physical age, a common concern of the balanced as well as the neurotic individuals, likely a good portion of the population. The relatively predictive and concrete information LabInTheWild is privy to, arrives in the form of survey answers. Which can be cross-matched for correlations.
The survey answers also serve as primary predictive factors, many alone likely larger than the vision data. As a group the answers must be at least an order of magnitude larger than the vision data. Hence they are used for age prediction as well, a sleight of hand that conceals the true predictive factors from the participant. The concealment is essential to protect the delusion that the participant is revealed to have a specific visual age, based on the color test, which they put most of their effort into. I wonder what the ethics of providing deceitful information is. The deceit is bothersome because it is so intelligently implemented, that it has some artistic value.
